And, in fact, bubbling errors up is very common in my code:<p><pre><code>    func (t *Thing) Delete() error {
        count, err := db.Delete(t)
        if err != nil {
            return err
        }
        if count != 1 {
            return errors.New(&quot;delete Thing didn&#x27;t delete 1 row? count: &quot; + string(count))
        }
        return nil
    }</code></pre>

I find that a mustBeNil function is useful:<p><pre><code>    func mustBeNil(err error) {
        if err != nil {
            panic(err)
            // or log.Fatal(err)
        }
    }
</code></pre>
or<p><pre><code>    func mustBeNil(err error, msg string) {
        if err != nil {
            log.Fatalf(&quot;%s: %s&quot;, err, msg)
        }
    }
</code></pre>
